Aug 9 2009 	Great Resort Excellent Value Will Stay Here Again!	Like many others, we booked here because of the extremely low rates; but we were not disappointed. The rooms might be described as larger than standard rooms at the Luxor, but not as large or luxurous as Mandalay Bay. Overall an excellent value, and we are already planning another extended weekend at this hotel.The rooms were very clean and comfortable, and this was the quietest hotel in which we have ever stayed. We heard absolutely nothing through the walls or floors during our entire stay, except for running water during early to mid-mornings, and this was only audible in our bathroom. The in-room safe was a nice convenience, though we left our diamond studs and other expensive jewelry and bundles of cash at home (just kidding).The food was very good at each restaurant we visited, and of particular note was the prime rib at Primarily Prime Rib, the crab legs and clam chowder at the Big Sur Oyster Bar, the biscuits and gravy in the Coronado Cafe, and about anything in the Del Mar Deli. The turnovers were each equivalent to about one-half of a fruit pie, and I am embarrassed to admit how many of those flaky pasteries we ate during our stay. Also, their sandwiches seem a little high in price, but they are HUGE!The pools (and the whole resort) is family friendly. The main pool area is actually three overlapping/connected pools. If I recall correctly, the two on the ends are graduated and only about 3 feet deep max, and the center pool was only 5 feet max. There were a lot of families there, but we didn't feel crowded.One day, we spent most of the afternoon in the multi-screen theater (seniors get in before 3 PM everyday for $3, using their Club Card). It was a nice break from the casino activities. Also, there is a 60 lane bowling alley next to the theater (both upstairs over the casino floor), but there was some kind of tournament going on when we looked in, with bleacher seats set up and only two people bowling. Also, there is a small arcade right outside the bowling alley, which had a pretty good, but limited assortment of the usual games.If you don't need the excitement of being on the strip, or you have a car and don't mind driving about 5 minutes to get to the action there, this might be the resort for you. We no longer consider Harrah's, the Luxor or Mandalay Bay in our Las Vegas plans, and South Point is our destination hotel of choice.	
