May 28 2009 	Great rooms big pool fun casino several restaurants easy to get to!	To say that South Point is south of the Strip is a bit of an understatement ... it's a good 5 miles south of MGM &amp; Luxor, which are at the south end of the Strip. Knowing that going in, South Point was a great value.We booked our room via Hotels.com for a Memorial Day weekend stay and got a rate about 40% less than through the hotel's website.Our room was spacious and clean, had a large sitting area, king bed, windows overlooking the pool, flat screen TV, in-room safe, and a huge bathroom. Considering that it sat above a rocking casino and the pool, it was perfectly quiet except for a bit of hallway noise at times...something experienced in all hotels.The casino offered a variety of table and slot/video poker games, had a large sports book, a bingo room, and a poker room. Table minimums were mainly $10, but even on this holiday weekend they kept a few $5 tables open all the time.Food at the three restaurants we ate at was good if not spectacular, but for the diner-range prices we paid, weren't a bad value.There were lots of poolside lounge chairs and plenty of room in the pool.The hotel also offers a spa; one of us took advantage of it and had a great massage there.If you're in Vegas to explore the Strip, the location is a bit limiting: the &quot;Deuce&quot; city bus doesn't go this far south and there's no shuttle to the Strip or downtown. But, if you have a car and a designated driver, its location right next to I-15 makes it an easy freeway drive to the big Strip casinos. Driving up the Strip from South Point was excruciatingly slow.Internet access is a steep $13/day, but who wants to check their e-mail when there are free cocktails in the casino?All in all, if the price here beats anything available on the Strip, we'd stay here again. But if we could find a comparable price at a hotel on the Strip with an outdoor pool, we'd probably pass.	
