Jan 22 2009 	Great bang for your buck.	Frequent visitors to Las Vegas, we've stayed at South Point a few times now. The renovations to the rooms are great; the rooms themselves look much more upscale than the hotel itself. The king bed was quite comfortable and the rooms offer good sound protection from the sometimes-noisy neighbors. The casino itself is nicer than some off the strip, but don't expect anything grand. The cocktail waitresses are a little slow, but friendly all around. I suspect several locals play here often. The food at their restaurant is actually quite good, the Chinese and bakery cafe especially. Valet is prompt and friendly. The location is close enough to the strip with a car--we go to a hotel on the strip and valet or park for free at most places anyway, and get out and walk or drive back. No shuttles, though, so if everyone is drinking plan on taxi rides. Pool is open year-round, though they will tell you in the winter there are no lifeguards, so swim at your own risk. Nice large area. Overall, a great clean, comfortable and relatively nice place to stay with rates about $100, it exceeds expectations for the price.	
Jan 21 2009 	Great Odds!	Our short (but intense) 2-night stay at the South Point was worth every penny, especially considering the great rate we obtained months ago. Their website does not lie and we found our room to be quite luxurious, compared to what we were previously used to. It was clean and everything worked just fine. The King size bed was very comfortable as were the oversized pillows. The bath products provided are really cool too. The shower aptly delivers. It’s great to have a 42” flat screen TV but the cable package is very (very) limited and not in HD so that sort of kills the deal a bit. The view from our room (5th floor) was a nice big cement wall. But we did not go to Vegas to stay in our room and watch TV so no big deal. Being away from the strip area is actually a plus because you’re not stuck in traffic when you’re heading back and it’s quieter all around. The casino itself seems just like any other and we don’t gamble so we can’t really advise you one way or the other. We had brunch at the Garden Buffet which was OK considering we used the two-for-one coupon given to us upon checking in. But I would have been reluctant to pay $13 for that quality of food. We also tried the Del Mar deli and as reported, one sandwich is good enough for two “normally proportioned” individuals. And satisfying enough for those with a BIG appetite. The convenience/gift/liquor shop is second to none for liquor prices. I had the opportunity to compare certain product prices with supermarket prices and South Point beat them by an average of 5-10% so there’s no need to drive elsewhere to get your libations. They obviously understand the concept of one-stop shopping and apply it without taking their guests for idiots (compared to places who charge airport-like prices). Overall, we would definitely return to the South Point providing such advantageous rates are still made available. If you’re renting a car, it’s the best deal in Vegas!Tip: if you booked Cirque du Soleil tickets in advance for pickup at the venue, don’t wait until show time to get them unless you’re sure to be there more than an hour before. If like us you go to Red Rock Canyon for the day and your plan is to swing by the venue around 16h00-16h30 to pick up your tickets (for the 19h00 show), go back to the South Point to freshen up and make it back to the strip, you might have a surprise. Because of the heavy traffic and the time it takes to make it to the venue, park, queue up for the tickets and finally have them in hand, you realize you’ll have no time to go back to the South Point, shower, drink a bit and come back. So instead, we got “stuck” having drinks at Wolfgang Puck (MGM) and paying airport prices. But it was fun anyway and we enjoyed every minute.	
