Dec 10 2008 	A Real Vegas Deal	I've now stayed at South Point (SP) five times, and the place keeps growing on me. (I was last there in July '08, and I'll be there again at the end of December '08.) I've stayed at many of Vegas's storied Strip hotels, from the Venetian to THEHotel and most of the big places in between, but for most of my frequent visits to Sin City, SP has become my hotel of choice. Why? My reasons are pretty much the same as those of my fellow TA reviewers: SP's excellent rooms, very low prices, and high standards of comfort and cleanliness. True, the hotel is only 3 years old, but it still seems brand new, no mean feat given its huge size and, er, less than high-end clientele. If you want glitz, glamour, and high prices, dozens of Vegas hotels can meet those desires. If, however, you want a spacious, very comfortable room that's quiet, relaxing, and well equipped, surf the web for SP's best room rates. (Hint: they're not usually found on the hotel's own web site, although SP promises to match any bonafide rate you find elsewhere; I had them make good on that promise once, and SP matched the rate I found on Expedia.) I've never paid more than $50 a night. At that rate, SP is a true Vegas bargain.A bit more on the rooms: at a minimum, you'll get a large room with a king or queen bed, a huge (42&quot;) plasma TV, and a great bathroom with the best amenities I've encountered in a Vegas hotel: Bath &amp; Body Works Coconut and Lime products -- they smell good enough to eat! The higher-floor rooms have great views over Vegas, the mountains, and/or the desert; SP's cottoned to the appeal of the higher-floor rooms and recently introduced a three-tier price scheme for its basic (&quot;Deluxe&quot;) rooms, charging more for &quot;mid&quot; and &quot;higher&quot; floors. Again, I recommend booking via a website other than the hotel's and then making your room request once you arrive; I've had good results doing so.SP's location is also, at least for me, a strong point. It's a few miles south of -- but only a few minutes by car via either LV Boulevard or I-15 from -- the Strip, and it's very easy to access and park at the hotel, something you can't say for most of the Strip properties. Unlike most huge Vegas hotels, SP has no discernible theme: it's bland, but in a pleasant, welcoming way; and I find the decor a welcome relief after dining and gambling at the sequined palaces on the Strip. SP's casino is airy and bright, and while it has as many smokers as any other big casino in Vegas, it seems less smoky. Even when crowded, there always seems to be enough space between you and all of the other gamblers and blinking machines.In short, SP deserves its hundreds of rave reviews and high ranking on TA. Give it a try, and I bet you'll appreciate your time on the Strip more by staying at South Point.	
Dec 1 2008 	loved it	Ok, so this is my second review now. We first stayed at Buffalo Bills in Primm. It was our first trip to las Vegas and we wanted to see it all. I would recommend doing it this way if you've never been it gives the opportunity to see the adjacent hotels and you don't feel like you're going too far from your hotel.Ok, now for the review. We arrived 3 hours early with the intention of gambling for a bit and then checking in. When we got to the desk checking in that early was NO problem. The counter staff was very nice and helpful. Make sure when you check in you get the coupon book for the hotel there are some great values in it. I think we used almost every coupon in the 3 days we stayed there, everything from buffet coupons, to bowling coupons. When we got up to the room we were amazed at the size and cleanliness of the room. We had a non smoking room, and to our surprise it didn't smell of smoke like the rest seem to. We had everything we needed in the room, a nice TV, a nice shower, and really nice beds. The view was not all that great as we were able to look at the building right beside, and nothing else but who goes to look out the window right? The pool and hot tub are just beautiful. Unfortunately they close at 5 pm so if you want to go for a swim make sure it's early. There were always clean towels out there, and I even felt safe leaving my stuff on a chair when I went to swim. The Casino is quite large and offered a nice variety of games. The service was really fast in the casino as well. Your drink was still cold when they got it to you. The gambling was good as well, some win some lose, I won I'm not saying millions, but I won enough to keep me in the casino and having a good time.The food choices are good, we ate the buffet which was probably the best we had all week in Vegas as far as selection and quality goes. We also ate at the deli, with a coupon from check in. Upon looking at the menu, it seems over priced but it's really not, the portions are just huge. We also did the bowling which was a lot of fun. With the coupon from check in 2 of us bowled 3 games for 13 dollars including shoe rental. This casino was the nicest we stayed at all week, the price was right and I'm already booking it for my return next year. But I will be staying there all week instead of bouncing around.	
