Oct 21 2008 	Very pleased will return	The reviews are basically right on for the South Point. I stayed 4 nights for a larger conference and enjoyed my stay. It was my first time staying off-strip and I will not hesitate to stay at the South Point again. Everything is priced better From $1 roulette minimums to drinks that are not going to set you back $8-$10 a pop. The coupon books they hand out upon check-in saved me at least $25 over the course of my stay.When not doing conference related activities, I enjoyed the bowling alley, sports book and gaming. Didn't have time to lay out by the pool, but from the looks of it, I would have gotten some nice relaxation if I had the time.At check-in, I asked for a room on a high floor and was given a room on the 24th floor (in the new wing) facing the strip. The room is large by any standard, with a spacious bathroom to match. I never seemed to wait more than 10 seconds for an elevator.Overall, I thought the food was good (both the buffet and the food served at the conference), but for a special night out something on the strip is still the best bet.As for the drawbacks, it is quite a bit off the strip as everyone has stated and I did hear some complaints about the shuttle. I rented a car and had no problem getting around. Parking is free almost everywhere on the Strip so no worries about parking there.And the smoke, it doesn't seem as the filtration system on the casino level is as good as other. But overall, just minor irritants.	
Oct 20 2008 	Loved South Point	Just got back from a weekend spent with some freinds at the South Point Resort and we loved it. This was the first time staying here. Check in was quick and easy and the staff friendly. I asked for a high room with a good view and was given a beautiful room with an amazing view in the new wing on the 20th floor facing the strip. The room was spotless and very well appointed. The bathroom was large and everything was decorated very nicely. I liked that the hallways were well lit and they have security officers at night checking for room keys before you can get on the elevators.The casino did seem a little smokier than normal but I think that is because there seemed to be a huge number of smokers compared to other casinos we visited. Very rarely could I sit at a machine without someone next to me lighting up. I didn't have this problem at the other casinos. I guess we just visited on a weekend with lots of smokers (I don't smoke, so I am very sensitive to it).The casino had a huge number of very fun penny slots. I like the penny slots because you can bet from 1 cent to $2.10 depending on your whim. I actually won some money this trip and there was a huge variety of machines to play on. The casino had a very fun vibe and everyone seemed to be relaxed and having a good time. The tables games were always pretty full and we were having fun with the slots so we didn't partake. We did play bingo in a really nice bingo hall and had a good time. We didn't visit the pool, bowling alley, or theatre, so I can't comment.We ate at Baja Miguels, which I didn't like the food at all, but my husband did. We ate at the buffet once and the coffee shop once. The food and service at both was good. My husband hung out at the casino bar while my girlfriend and I gambled and he had a great time with the bartenders who he said were very friendly and personable. He said one bartender even took the time to teach a patron how to play the video poker machine. Most of the staff we encountered were very friendly and helpful except for one cashier in the gift shop who was extremely surly, but she was the one bad apple and everyone else was great.I would highly recommend this hotel to anyone visiting Las Vegas. It is not as hectic as hotels on the strip and if you want to go there it was only a 10 minute drive. The rooms are very nice and spacious, the staff friendly, and the casino was great. We loved it.	
