Oct 5 2008 	Enjoyable stay	Just back from a week at South Point which turned out to be just as advertised-very enjoyable. If you've ever stayed at The Orleans, you will know what to expect, as it is very similar, and used to be part of the same group. I'd score it higher than The Orleans on having a very straightforward layout, and, in particular, a much less smoky casino. I'd perhaps score it lower on the buffet, which I could only describe as average. I sampled a few other of the food places and found them all to be of good quality at very reasonable prices. There is a free shuttle to the airport and also to The Mandalay Bay, on The Strip. They don't really advertise The Strip shuttle and you have to find the casino entrance by the parking garage for the pick up point, but it did run every 30 minutes and was only about a ten minute ride. The temperature was in the mid nineties so I really enjoyed relaxing by the pool every day. Nothing fancy but very pleasant, clean and well maintained. The room itself was great. Very comfortable king size bed, nice bathroom, very quiet but efficient air conditioning and perfectly cleaned by the room staff every day. 42&quot; TV on the wall was good for watching the Baseball Playoffs (shame it wasn't in HD though). The only downer on the room (5th floor) was that my &quot;view&quot; was the wall of another building, so perhaps you should mention that when you book, if you do want to see something/anything out the window. The casino was well laid out with a good selection of games. I stick to slots and video poker and ended up spending only half my budget. It's worth joining The Players Club as I got back over $120 by the end of my week. A few reviews have mentioned poor service, but I can honestly say that I had no problem at all with any of the staff. They all seemed friendly and efficient. In general the place appears to be well run. The first half of the week there were mostly middle aged and elderly visitors with some families and children. Later in the week there was a Native American rodeo event at the equestrian centre. As a Brit I found this most interesting as many of them wore Cowboy hats (not like in those old movies) and also spoke in their own languages. As far as I could see, everyone from whatever background got on very well together, and had a good time in the nice relaxed atmosphere in the casino.  It is true that South Point is a few miles south of the main Strip, so if you want to be in the middle of all the action, this is probably not the place for you. But if you are looking for good quality at a reasonable price I can thoroughly recommend this hotel/casino to you.	
