Sep 25 2008 	Excellent Value but not without a few minor flaws...	I had heard positive things about South Point and decided to give it a try for a few nights. I had never really stayed off strip in Vegas, ( only the Orleans which is very close) but the rates were so low and the place looked nice so I gave it a shot. Lets start with the positives since they far outweight the negatives. The exterior of the hotel is very grand-- Much like any nice hotel on the strip. One postive thing we realized right away is that this hotel is not complicated in its layout, unlike many of the other big resorts that feel like mazes at times. The check-in counter is right near the entrance, and you enter right into the casino. The casino is nice and spacious, well lit, and has an airy and open feel about it. Finding our room was very simple, and not a long hike. Basically thats the way the entire hotel felt. Even though its a big place, everything feels nearby and easy to find. We got a mid-level room.. it was on the 17th floor and provided a good view of the pool and mountains. I would advise others to pay the extra 10$ or so a night and get a room with a good view. As far as the room itself, it was great! Huge and very well decorated. Probably the best room I have ever seen for that price. It had a very large bathroom with the always desired seperate vanity area. No complaints about the room whatsoever. One of the other biggest postives about the south point is their pool. Its not the grandest or most decadent in Vegas by any stretch, but its still very nice. And what made it even greater for me was the lack of crowds. Even on Satruday the pool was at most half full. You had your choice of chairs. And on Tuesday it almost felt like we had the pool to ourselves. South Point also has a great selection of restaruants. We tried about 3 or 4 of them.Now for a few negatives. For one, I thought the buffet was quite lousy. Even on Sunday morning. The selection was mediocre and the food did not taste fresh.Kind of a downer. Also they were playing loud music at 830am. Thats the last thing you want to hear while eating breakfast hungover in Vegas. The Black jack dealers were among the least friendly I have ever come across. One guy almost frightened me he seemed so angry. This is not a knock against the casino itself, just the people they seem to hire. The sportsbook was excellent, but VERY crowded on Sunday for football. Almost impossible to get a seat. And there were hundereds of them. And one more minor complaint is about the shuttle to strip. For some reason it only takes you to Mandalay Bay. Which is great if you are going there or right nearby, but most people end up going to the center strip. So you either had to pay another 10-15$ for cab to take you farther down, or walk the 20-30mins in the heat. We chose the taxi. I really think they should extend the shuttle to take people a little further up-- maybe to the Flamingo.All in all its a excellent value, and we had a great time. Like any place it has a few flaws, but for that price we both were very pleased with what we experienced at South Point.	
Sep 25 2008 	Vegastastic!!	I had visted Vegas previously and I must admit, I had my reservations about staying &quot;off The Strip&quot;. On arrival all those reservations quickly dissapeared. The South Point is absolutely superb. This hotel is enormous but luxuriuos. Yes, its quite a way off the Strip but the hotel provides modern air-conditioned courtesy buses that run throughout the day, up to half a dozen times an hour. You are never waiting for more than ten minutes for a bus to turn up and whip you down to the Madalay Bay. Pickups from the Strip run much later into the evening than other lesser-hotels situated Off-Strip. The South Point has just undergone a major extension and refurb and looks simply stunning against the backdrop of the Nevada desert. However, even though the work had not yet been finished when we visted eralier this year there was no noisy or dust. The only gripe I had was that the simming pool was closed and the hotel didn't offer any alternative or made provisions at a sister hotel. Everything else was WorldClass. The major advantage of Off-Strip are the sunrise and sunsets, simply spectacular and breathtaking. Price? Well value for money doesn't come into it. This is better than value for money! This is the cheapest luxury hotel I have ever had the fortune to stay in. Forget the Luxor or the MGM, when I'm coming back it will be the South Point everytime!!! :)	
