Aug 5 2008 	Big Rooms	I knew this place was going to be away from the strip, so I was expecting the worst. The hotel is new and big, and in a quiet area that looks very safe. I was surprised to see how big the room was. The restaurants in the hotel offer a good deal, and the discount / freebies coupon book is pretty good that you get at check-in, since it included a free bottle of wine with dinner. There is a lot of free parking, and there is a free shuttle bus to and from the airport and the strip. I think the airport bus runs hourly, so check. While we were there, many NASCAR teams stayed there, and there was a cattle show going on. The security is pretty tight at the hotel, and a guard is posted in the evenings by the elevator. The only thing that took long was the check in line at the front desk. But I forgot about that as I started walking around and seeing the theaters and bowling alleys, and all the other stuff going. I was pleasantly surprised, and would stay there again because of the value.	
Aug 3 2008 	What value for money	Stayed here for a week and was really suprised about how good the hotel was. My experience was that it was very clean, staff very helpful and very good facilities (pool, cinema, bowling alley, restaurants) . From the time we arrived and just walked straight up to the check-in (no queue) to the time we checked out (again no queue) we had a really nice time. Having stayed on the main strip before (Mirage, Luxor and Alladin, now Planet Hollywood) this hotel is far better value, not just because of the excellent price but the levels of facilities and service. They provide a free shuttle service to the strip (Mandalay Bay Hotel) and from there you can take the deuce bus to anywhere on the strip or take the free mono rail to the excalibur hotel further up the strip. They also provide a free shuttle service to and from the airport (saving $25 to $30 each way, compard to getting a taxi). Would stay in this hotel again without a moments hesitation.	
Aug 2 2008 	South Point GOES Circus Circus	We stayed @ SP from 7-23 through 7-31. Problems right off the bat with check-in as we had two reservations, one for two days on a promotion and one for the balance. Clerk can't find the first reservation says to come back in an hour so that the person I worked with on the reservation will be on site. Go back in 1 1/2 hour and find the person I worked with and she finds reservation. She can't understand why the 1st clerk could not find it. Room is good but here is where Circus circus comes in. I guess because SP opened the additional 800 rooms on 7-21 the majority of guests seem to be teenagers in various sports tournaments. For eight days the crowds both inside and outside the casino are packed with kids. Gang graffiti scratched on the elevator doors, I was in the casino @ 3:00 am with crowds of teenagers walking here and there with no adults with them, even though signs throughout the casino say no one under 18 is allowed in the SP unsupervised after 9:00 pm weekdays and 10:00 pm weekends. One afternoon after spending 1/2 hour @ the pool, which felt like the pool in Caddyshack on caddy day, I counted 23 people in the baby pool. These were people in the water not just setting on the side. Baby pool maybe 20' in diameter. Again, I think because of the additional rooms, the facilities are taxed beyond limits as the pool is same size, restaurants have not increased either in size or number. To SP's credit, they are building 3 new restaurants but that work is continuing and no word on when it will be opening. I have always agreed that SP was a hidden jewel in LV but please be aware of the potential issues with the new rooms and limited facilities and staff to support the expansion. Hopefully SP will be getting it's act together shortly and the kids will be back in school come fall and winter.	
