May 21 2008 	Wonderful!1	After an exhausting search for a honeymoon hotel it came to a toss up between the South Point, The Orleans or the Red Rock. We finally plumped for the South Point....and we are glad we did!!!The room was wonderful, a beautiful view of the mountains large and very clean. The hotel as a whole was also very clean, the staff very friendly and helpful check in and check out was very smooth.Excellent restaurants, wonderful room service and a great casino!We would definitely go back there again!!	
May 20 2008 	A Perfect Fit for our Vegas Vacation	As a first-timer to Vegas and a non-gambler, I was more excited about seeing the sites and experiencing the thrills.... from a distance. My husband found this hotel. We loved the price and appreciated that it was just a few minutes off of the strip.The hotel is enormous and even still it's growing. There was an entire wing still under construction. (The construction didn't disrupt our stay. We didn't hear a thing.) Our room was more than spacious, the bathroom was clean and stocked with Bath &amp; Body Works product. The bed was comfortable. The room was quiet. We over-looked the pool. But a couple weeks before the trip we were informed our rate dropped $10/night. When we arrived we realized why... the pool was closed. Darn. But it looked nice!We ate at Michael's. It was pricey -to say the least- but well worth it. We enjoyed our meals and the extra &quot;courses&quot; that we didn't expect (large relish tray while we cruised the menu, sorbet before the entree, and chocolate covered fruit with the check). It was truly high-class. Next time I won't wear jeans and flip-flops! Still the service treated us like we were royalty. Save your winnings and spend it here!	
May 19 2008 	Love this hotel!!	This is the third time that we have stayed at this hotel and we love it!The hotel is about 5 miles from the Strip, but as we don't go to Vegas for the casinos, it suits us fine. There is a regular shuttle from the hotel (every 15ish minutes) to the Mandalay Bay, so it's easy to get to the Strip.The rooms are large, modern and clean and all have a LARGE screened TV.There are several places to eat at the hotel, the breakfast and dinner are both excellent value.Staff have always been very helpful and friendly.The hotel is currently being extended (to include another 800 rooms), but even though we saw the builders accessing the stairwells, they did not pose any problems. There are notices apologising to guests for the presence of dust due to the building work.It's easy to get to the Car Rental Returns from the hotel, and there is also an airport shuttle.We will definitely use this hotel again!	
May 19 2008 	Low priced but several miles frin the main strip	This casino resort is located several miles south of the Las Vegas strip. Because of its location, a car or use of taxis is necessary if you really want to enjoy Vegas. The hotel does offer complimentary shuttle service to Mandalay Bay.The hotel is about 2 years old and the property is in good shape. Although advertised as “affordable luxury” (with the rooms at $53 it is definitely affordable), this is a 3 star resort and definitely lacks the charm of many of the strip properties. No themes or grand entrances. Check-in was quick during this midweek May stay. Staff was friendly. The workout facility ($10 per day) and the spa (another $5 per day) are above par with plenty of equipment in the gym. The men’s spa was clean and had what you would expect with a sauna, steam room and a couple of hot / cool tub options. The pool was closed for new construction. Although I did not seem them, there is an equestrian center, bowling alley and movie theater on site. There are several restaurant choices but only ate at Coronado’s Café (coffee shop) and the Del Mar Deli. Both were fair. There are several casino bars around but no real nightlife and no clubs. It looked like one of the casino bars was setup for a band but none was playing that I saw. Tried The Social House at TI for dinner and thought it was overpriced and not that great; ESPN Zone at NY NY is a great choice for bar type food and watching the games.The casino had plenty of $5 tables and it was easy to get a seat. Beverage service was also plentiful. The rooms are large and have nice HD TVs, comfortable bedding, a desk area and a decent sized bathroom. The view from the 6th floor was non-existent so if you want to see something out the window, you may want to go higher.Overall, this is a decent option for budget minded travelers that have a car and are willingly to head out for better dining and nightlife.	
May 16 2008 	Very nice 	I had originally planned on staying on the strip, but checked out this hotel when I found out it's new. New hotels are always nicer.Hotel is new about 2.5 years old &amp; nice. The casino is well-lit, the rooms are spacious &amp; well appointed. This hotel looks exactly like the pictures on its website &amp; photos other guests have posted.Registration is directly across the casino &amp; as previous guests have commented, you must go through the casino to get to the elevators to go up to your room. The casino is smoky as expected. However, if you're just wanting to go up to your room or leave the hotel, walking through the casino is not that bad.Parking is free &amp; you can park in the parkade or park outside in front of the hotel. We parked outside &amp; had no problems finding a spot. Valet parking is $9. Upon arrival there's Valet help in unloading &amp; taking luggage to your room. They take down your name, take your luggage &amp; give you a receipt. Once you've finished checking in &amp; are in your room, dial the Bell Desk from your phone &amp; they'll deliver your luggage.Upon checking in, you get a coupon book that has discounts for the restaurants, 2-for-1 buffet, free gift (3 gold-looking mardi gras bead necklaces), 10% off Seatle's Best coffee, etc. The 2-for-1 buffet was good. Chinese food at the Coronado cafe was very bad so avoid it. Food was too salty, had too much MSG (monosodium glutamate) &amp; didn't taste fresh at all. The won ton soup was so chewy that I though I was eating bubble gum, come on. Avoid Seatle's Best Coffee, the Phillipino ladies in the morning were extremely rude &amp; had poor customer service skills. Another customer saw one of them discreetly spit in someone's coffee after the guy complained she handed him the wrong coffee twice. Be careful if you decide to get coffee here. The bar at the casino also serves coffee, hot water, etc. &amp; it's free drinks (tip the waitress $1) if you're playing at the casino. There's a McDonalds a couple minutes North of the hotel, too.Sign up to receive the hotel's discount sent to your email address. Go to http://southpointcasino.com &amp; click the button on the bottom left of the screen &quot;Sign Up Now for Exclusive Email Offers&quot;. I had already made my reservation, but signed up anyway. About 2 weeks later, I received a discount code sent to my email address for 25% off the posted rate. I called reservation, mentioned the discount code &amp; they adjusted my rate. I got 1 room with 2 queen beds for $53/night weekdays &amp; $112.50/weekend. The posted rates were $73/night weekdays &amp; $150/night weekends. Not sure if the discount code (EDEAL28) still works, give it a try. Upon checking out, they gave me a coupon for 20% off the posted rate for a return visit. The discount code is BBK1106 &amp; expires June 30/08. Mention these discount codes when you make your reservation. I made my reservation on the hotel's website.The room is huge with 2 queen beds, a big LCD screen TV, a desk &amp; chair, a large dresser, coffee maker &amp; coffee. The bathtub &amp; toilet are in an enclosed room right behind the sink/vanity. Lots of counter space. There is no fan in the bathroom so you might want to leave the door open while taking a shower otherwise, all the steam will build up &amp; fog the mirror.Toiletries are from Bath &amp; Body Works. They include shampoo, conditioner, shower gel, lotion &amp; a bar soap. The shampoo, conditioner, shower gel &amp; lotion are large size for hotel toiletries (59 mL or 2 fl oz). For those who love Bath &amp; Body Works' products, the scent of toiletries is coconut lime verbena. It's a fresh lime smell &amp; not much of the coconut.The business centre has computers, but internet is $10.99/hour charged to your credit card. However, a couple minutes drive North of the hotel is the Clark County Library where you can check your email for free. There's a computer that allows 15 minutes access anytime or you could ask the librarian for a temporary card &amp; get 1 hour of free internet when booked in advanced.Next to the library, is Food 4 Less where you could get groceries &amp; water. Next to that is the Las Vegas Outlet Centre &amp; a strip mall with restaurants.The hotel, despite being South of the strip is convenient &amp; not super busy. We rented a car &amp; it took about 20 minutes from the hotel to the North end of the strip (The Wynn hotel). It took about 15 minutes to get to the airport. I did notice guests smoking in the elevators &amp; on non-smoking floors despite signs that said no smoking. The Bell Desk can loan wheelchairs for use within the hotel for free. It's $25/week if the wheelchair is taken out of the hotel.I highly recommend this hotel because it's new, very clean &amp; the rooms are wonderful. Ask for a roomaway from construction to avoid the noise. I didn't hear anything except for some hammer pounding sound for about 5 minutes one morning. The hotel is adding 800 more rooms so if you're staying here later in the year, ask for the newer room &amp; it will probably be even better.If you want to avoid the casino &amp; smoke altogether, stay at new Hilton Garden Inn a couple minutes North of this hotel near the Las Vegas Outlet Centre. It has no casino &amp; includes fridge/microwave in the room, but I think the rate is higher than what South Point charges. Do try the buffet at Spice Market restaurant in the Miracle Miles shop at Planet Hollywood. It's $17.99/person for lunch &amp; it's very yummy. There's Asian, Mexican, Japanese, Indian, Italian cuisine, salad bar, seafood, ribs, soup, desserts. There's a lot of variety &amp; it was one of the best meals we had in Vegas.	
May 15 2008 	Good Choice	We were in Vegas for the Interop Convention held at Mandalay Bay. Last year we stayed at Mandalay and were very disappointed - long check in, couldn't get near the pools, worn room, TV in bathroom didn't work, lots of noise from hallway, etc. definitely not worth the price. So, this year we decided to stay off the strip as we always rent a car so that was not a problem. SP does have shuttles to the strip and airport. Check in was a breeze and we were given a coupon book plus we got extra points at the slot club since both our birthdays were in April and we stayed there during our birthday month. Plus they had a members promotion going on one day and we got 2 T-shirts and a nice Thermos set. The staff were extremely friendly and service oriented. We checked in early and they put us in a room away from the construction. Not much of a view but the room was quiet and like new with a large, flat screen TV. Another nice feature was that the bathtub/shower and toilet are in a separate room from the vanity/sink area so we could both get ready at the same time. The only negative was that the pool was closed due to the construction but it is supposed to be open for the summer.We used a coupon from the book for a 2 for 1 breakfast buffet which was good. We also shared a huge sandwich at the Deli one day which was very good. They also had gigantic pastries. The dinner buffet was just average. One morning we had breakfast in the Del Mar Cafe which was also very good. They also have a Steakhouse and Mexican restaurant which we never got to try. The Sports Book had 75 cent Vienna hot dogs.There are numerous bars with nightly entertainment. We had originally planned to go to the Bill Medley/Paul Revere and the Raiders show but had a change in plans.The casino has ample slot machines and tables with low limits. Quite a few times the whole place would be humming when we walked in from the parking garage and we would just have to stop and play and it paid off nicely a few times.South Point is definitely not suffering from the cutbacks, rude employees and low payouts I keep reading about at the Strip casinos. For 1/4 the price of what we'd have paid for Mandalay this was a real deal and we'd definitely stay here again.	
